    "instruction": "Using the metric anomaly table already computed (global P95/P05 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) computed on full series and filtered incident-window records with an 'is_anomaly' flag), detect consecutive anomaly runs per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) within 2022-03-20 09:00:00 to 09:30:00 (UTC+8). For each run where run_length >= 2 (i.e., exclude isolated single-point spikes) produce one compact row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_timestamp (first anomalous point dt), run_end_timestamp (last anomalous point dt), run_length (count of consecutive anomalous minutes), anomaly_direction ('high' if value>global_p95 else 'low' if value<global_p05), max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, global_p95, global_p05, severity_percent (for 'high' = (max_value - global_p95)/max(1e-9,global_p95)*100; for 'low' = (global_p05 - min_value)/max(1e-9,global_p05)*100). Sort results by severity_percent desc, then run_start_timestamp asc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Store full run table in kernel variables but return only the compact top-20 table described."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected frontend traces for 09:00–09:05 and found brief trace P95/mean exceedances around 09:00–09:02 (frontend-2 -> productcatalogservice at 09:00:00; frontend-0 -> adservice ~09:01). Error logs show frontend warnings from 09:00:01. Metric-run detection identified an early, high-severity node-level fault: node-1 system.cpu.iowait run at 09:00:00–09:01 with ~404% severity. Other high-severity runs (network bursts) occur later (09:19–09:28) and likely represent separate transient spikes. To decide root cause we must know which physical nodes host the frontend pods (are frontends on node-1 or on other nodes such as node-5 or node-6?). If the frontends run on node-1 and node-1 had an immediate severe iowait/CPU spike at 09:00:00, that strongly implicates node-1 as the root cause. If frontends run on other nodes (e.g., node-5), then node-1's early spike may be unrelated and the frontends (with many errors) may instead indicate a container/service-level issue. Therefore the next step is: map frontend pods to node ids using their metric kpi_name patterns (e.g., 'container.node-5.*') and then check node-level consecutive anomaly runs near the incident start (09:00–09:05) for those nodes to see whether any of them had early, high-severity runs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From the metric DataFrame, for each frontend pod in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2] extract node identifiers present in their kpi_name strings by finding patterns like 'container.node-<N>' (report the top node token per pod and its count). Limit to at most top 5 node tokens per pod.\n2) From the metric-run 'runs' table (the consecutive anomaly runs computed earlier), filter runs for cmdb_id in the set of node tokens found above (e.g., node-1,node-5,...) and run_start_timestamp between 2022-03-20 09:00:00+08:00 and 2022-03-20 09:05:00+08:00. Return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, run_start_timestamp, run_end_timestamp, run_length, kpi_name, anomaly_direction, severity_percent, sorted by severity_percent desc. Limit to top 20 rows.\nReturn both the frontend->node mapping and the filtered node-run table (each compact and bounded). Store results in kernel variables for later steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We mapped all three frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2) to node-5. Node-5 shows short, low-severity memory/disk anomalies at 09:00:00–09:01, but the severity is small (<1%). The earliest and strongest symptom remains the error_logs concentrated on frontend pods beginning at 2022-03-20 09:00:01+08:00. Trace spikes from frontends to productcatalogservice/adservice/recommendationservice are brief around 09:00–09:02. Other high-severity metric runs (node-1 CPU iowait at 09:00) appear unrelated because frontends run on node-5. Given many frontend error log entries starting immediately at 09:00:01 and the trace spikes shortly after, the root cause is likely at the frontend level (container or process) or something on node-5 affecting frontend containers. To distinguish container/process-level faults from node-level resource issues, we need more detail from logs: the exact error messages from error_logs.csv for frontend pods and the per-minute aggregated log.error_count from log.csv for the frontend pods during the incident window. This will help identify whether frontends encountered repeated application errors (e.g., failed to retrieve..., timeouts, process crashes) at the start of the incident or whether the issue was more resource-related on node-5.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From error_logs.csv, for cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2] return a compact table with: cmdb_id, total_error_rows, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, and top 5 distinct message text snippets with their counts (limit 5 messages per cmdb_id). Also include for each top message one sample timestamp (earliest). 2) From log.csv filter log_name == 'log.error_count' and cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2] and incident window 2022-03-20 09:00:00 to 2022-03-20 09:30:00 (UTC+8). For each frontend pod return: cmdb_id, sum_error_count_over_window, max_error_count_minute, earliest_minute_with_error_count>0 (or null), number_of_minutes_with_error_count>0. Limit output to these three rows (one per frontend). Store results in kernel variables but return only the compact tables described."
}

